  "bench_knowledge": [
    {
      "rule_id": "light_protect_sensitive",
      "because": "Light-sensitive reagents degrade under UV or visible light by different mechanisms depending on the compound class. Fluorophores (DAPI, ethidium bromide) undergo irreversible photobleaching \u2014 the chromophore is destroyed; 30 seconds of UV transilluminator exposure causes measurable DAPI signal loss. Oxidizers (H\u2082O\u2082, NaOCl) photodecompose, losing titer. Peroxide-forming solvents (diethyl ether) form hydroperoxides faster in light. Light-activated monomers (acrylamide) can begin polymerising spontaneously. Amber containers or foil-wrap block the relevant wavelengths for all of these.",
      "cite": "Thermo Fisher Scientific: DAPI Technical Data Sheet (D1306). Lakowicz, Principles of Fluorescence Spectroscopy, 3rd ed., Ch. 1. Sigma-Aldrich H\u2082O\u2082 Product Information (216763).",
      "confidence": "high"
    }
  ],
